              <span id="reviewTextContainer4104460291" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4289229725598786100">‘People just don’t know what to say or do when someone has cancer.’ - Advice<br/>Idaho author Lynda Wolters works in a law firm and in addition to her love of sports and outdoor activities, she volunteers in places where she can be of service to people. She was diagnosed with stage 4 mantle cell lymphoma in 2016, and since that time has devoted her attention to being available to other cancer patient friends. Her initial publication was VOICES OF LGBTQ+: A Conversation Starter for Understanding, Supp</span>
  <span id="freeText4289229725598786100" style="display:none">‘People just don’t know what to say or do when someone has cancer.’ - Advice<br />Idaho author Lynda Wolters works in a law firm and in addition to her love of sports and outdoor activities, she volunteers in places where she can be of service to people. She was diagnosed with stage 4 mantle cell lymphoma in 2016, and since that time has devoted her attention to being available to other cancer patient friends. Her initial publication was VOICES OF LGBTQ+: A Conversation Starter for Understanding, Supporting, and Protecting Gay, Bi, Trans and Queer People – a sensitive response to her concern for her gay son’s travails, and now she adds VOICES OF CANCER to her repertoire. <br />Lynda’s fine book addresses all the phases and regions of thought and response that cancer patients encounter – Part On: Initial Reactions, Part Two: Surviving Treatment, Part Three: Forward into the New Normal, and Part Four: Life is Short…for Everyone. In each section she shares the views of the Patient and the Non-Patient – a very sensitive manner of exploring the vantages of both the person with cancer and those with whom the patient comes in contact, a well-considered approach to fully appreciate each subject covered. And as a sound follow up to this approach, at the book’s end she offers tips and reminders for both the Patient and for the Non-Patient! In addition she provides a fine section on cancer terminology that deserves exploring.<br />In her Preface Lynda shares her reason for writing this book of conversations with cancer patients along with her own responses from symptoms to diagnosis to treatment to prognosis: ‘It was only when I was diagnosed that I truly understood the full extent of the need for support, both for the patient and the caregiver. Emotional support is a necessary and vital component to a person’s overall sense of well-being. This couldn’t be truer in the face of a cancer diagnosis…Cancer is terrifying to the patient and to the people around them. It is touching people every day and truly is a part of life. You can support your loved ones who suffer with it by reaching out to them with the small things that matter…I was encouraged by dozens of people, including doctors, nurses, patients, and caregivers, to write about the tough subjects that relate to cancer. The inner thoughts we cancer patients do not really share: the fear, the twisted humor, the newfound insight following the acceptance of the diagnosis, and the wish for others to appreciate the beauty that comes when clarity and perspective move together in the right direction.’<br />This little book is illuminating – thoughts shared on a level rarely encountered and greatly needed by all of us who will eventually be confronted with either the disease of cancer or the recognition of family or friends who are struggling with that potentially terminal illness. This is an excellent resource for ‘patients and non-patients’ to use Lynda’s terms. Highly recommended. Grady Harp, July 21<br />Claire Small<br />‘People just don’t know what to say or do when someone has cancer.’ - Advice<br /><br />Idaho author Lynda Wolters works in a law firm and in addition to her love of sports and outdoor activities, she volunteers in places where she can be of service to people. She was diagnosed with stage 4 mantle cell lymphoma in 2016, and since that time has devoted her attention to being available to other cancer patient friends. Her initial publication was VOICES OF LGBTQ+: A Conversation Starter for Understanding, Supporting, and Protecting Gay, Bi, Trans and Queer People – a sensitive response to her concern for her gay son’s travails, and now she adds VOICES OF CANCER to her repertoire. <br /><br />Lynda’s fine book addresses all the phases and regions of thought and response that cancer patients encounter – Part On: Initial Reactions, Part Two: Surviving Treatment, Part Three: Forward into the New Normal, and Part Four: Life is Short…for Everyone. In each section she shares the views of the Patient and the Non-Patient – a very sensitive manner of exploring the vantages of both the person with cancer and those with whom the patient comes in contact, a well-considered approach to fully appreciate each subject covered. And as a sound follow up to this approach, at the book’s end she offers tips and reminders for both the Patient and for the Non-Patient! In addition she provides a fine section on cancer terminology that deserves exploring.<br /><br />In her Preface Lynda shares her reason for writing this book of conversations with cancer patients along with her own responses from symptoms to diagnosis to treatment to prognosis: ‘It was only when I was diagnosed that I truly understood the full extent of the need for support, both for the patient and the caregiver. Emotional support is a necessary and vital component to a person’s overall sense of well-being. This couldn’t be truer in the face of a cancer diagnosis…Cancer is terrifying to the patient and to the people around them. It is touching people every day and truly is a part of life. You can support your loved ones who suffer with it by reaching out to them with the small things that matter…I was encouraged by dozens of people, including doctors, nurses, patients, and caregivers, to write about the tough subjects that relate to cancer. The inner thoughts we cancer patients do not really share: the fear, the twisted humor, the newfound insight following the acceptance of the diagnosis, and the wish for others to appreciate the beauty that comes when clarity and perspective move together in the right direction.’<br /><br />This little book is illuminating – thoughts shared on a level rarely encountered and greatly needed by all of us who will eventually be confronted with either the disease of cancer or the recognition of family or friends who are struggling with that potentially terminal illness. This is an excellent resource for ‘patients and non-patients’ to use Lynda’s terms. Highly recommended. <br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="4289229725598786100" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


