<div id="review_2983254406" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2983254406" />
    <a title="Cody" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/102984727-cody"><img alt="Cody" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2983254406?book_show_action=true">Sep 19, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Cody" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Cody" href="/user/show/102984727-cody">Cody</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2983254406" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17593752632787989150">This book is a wonderful and well-written read. It&apos;s partly a behind-the-scenes look at what cancer patients go through, but also gives patients and loved ones an idea of what to expect during treatment. It&apos;s a helpful guide for those who don&apos;t know what to say or don&apos;t know what to do when a friend or loved one receives a cancer diagnosis. What I found stunning, and caused me some self-reflection, is that too often friends disappear when a patient is going through treatment because they don&apos;t k</span>
  <span id="freeText17593752632787989150" style="display:none">This book is a wonderful and well-written read. It's partly a behind-the-scenes look at what cancer patients go through, but also gives patients and loved ones an idea of what to expect during treatment. It's a helpful guide for those who don't know what to say or don't know what to do when a friend or loved one receives a cancer diagnosis. What I found stunning, and caused me some self-reflection, is that too often friends disappear when a patient is going through treatment because they don't know what to say or they don't know what to do. How often do people say, "Let me know if you need anything" but never follow up, assuming help isn't needed because the request never came? Lynda Wolters has a gift for writing. I highly recommend this book.<br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="17593752632787989150" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


